column168: Description Of Events

FOUR 55 GALLON DRUMS LOADED ON FLOOR IN FRONT OF SKID.  FORKLIFT PUNCTURED BOTTOM OF DRUM WHEN MOVING THE SKID LOADED DIRECTLY BEHIND THE DRUMS. COUNSELLING AND CONTINUED TRAINING WILL BE PROVIDED TO BETTER LOAD/UNLOAD AND PROTECT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

AFTER SERVICING CUSTOMER PARTS WASHER, I PLACED DRUM OF WASTE SOLVENT AT REAR OF VEHICLE FOR LOADING.  BEFORE LOADING I WENT TO CUSTOMER AND FINISHED FILLING OUT THE PAPER WORK.  I THEN WENT TO THE CAB TO PUT THE PAPERWORK AWAY AND AS I WENT TO SIT IN DRIVERS SEAT I ACCIDENTALLY KNOCKED GEAR SHIFT OUT OF GEAR.  BEFORE I COULD APPLY THE BRAKE THE TRUCK HAD ROLLED BACK AND HE KNOCKED THE DRUM OVER.  APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON LEAKED OUT OF THE SEAL IN THE LID.  I IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE SPILL AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL SOLVENT.  THE INCIDENT TOOK PLACE ON THE CUSTOMERS ASPHALTED PARKING LOT.  IN THE FUTURE I WILL BE LOADING AS SOON AS I BRING DRUMS TO MY TRUCK.

AT THIS POINT, THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH SORBENT PADS; AND THEN; CLEANED UP WITH CORN-COB ABSORBNENT AND "SORBENT PADS".  NO WATERWAYS WERE PRESENT, AND ALL MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED.

column168: OUR TANK TRUCK AND TANK TRAILER LOADED WITH UNLEADED GASOLINE ROLLED OVER WHILE MANEUVERING THROUGHT AN "S" CURVE ON HIGHWAY 68 IN MONTEREY, CALIFORNIA.  PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE DAMAGED TANKS AND CAUGHT ON FIRE. THE DRIVER ESCAPED SERIOUS INNURY.  HE HAD A SMALL CUT ON HIS FOREHEAD THAT REQUIRED 4 STITCHES.  POST ACCIDENT DRUG TESTING WAS DONE AND THE DRIVER'S TEST WAS NEGATIVE.  THE INCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED AND REPORTED TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WITHIN MINUTES.  THE FIRE WAS PUT OUT WITHIN ABOUT AN HOUR.  SOIL WAS CONTAMINATED AND REMEDIATION AND REMOVAL STARTED THE NEXT DAY.  A THROUGH INVESTIGATION WAS CONDUCTED AND RECOMMENDATIONS FOR PREVENTION OF FUTURE OCCURRANCES WERE MADE.  THEY INCLUDE REFRESHER TRAINING, DISCIPLINE AS NECESSARY, WARNINGS OF ROAD AREAS SUCH AS THIS ONE.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING A PALLET OF FREIGHT, WE DISCOVERED ONE BOX OF PRODUCT WITH THE CARDBOARD SOAKED.  THIS CARTON HAD FALLEN DOWN THROUGH THE PALLET AND HAD BEEN STRUCK BY THE FORKLIFT FORK.  TWO OUT OF THE FOUR BOTTLES INSIDE HAD BEEN PUNCTURED OPEN.  ONE WAS STILL ALMOST FULL AND THE OTHER WAS APPROXIMATELY HALF FULL.  WE THEN POURED THE REMAINING QUANTITIES OF THE PRODUCT OUT OF THE BAD BOTTLES, INTO A NEW LARGE PLASTIC BOTTLE.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS THEN NOTIFIED AND AGREED TO TAKE DELIVERY ON THE REMAINING PRODUCT, INCLUDING THE PRODUCT AND THAT WAS LEFT OVER FROM THE TWO BROKEN BOTTLES.  THE EMPTY BOTTLES AND CARDBOARD FROM THE BOX WERE DISCARDED IN THE TRASH DUMPSTER.  NO OTHER CLEAN UP WAS NEEDED.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS WE MUST BETTER INSPECT THE PALLETS WE RECEIVE FROM SHIPPERS.

LEAKING DRUM DISCOVERED AT TIME TO UNLOAD FREIGHT.  DRUM WAS LEAKING ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  DRUM WAS THEN TURNED UPSIDE DOWN TO EXPOSE CRACK WHERE LEAKAGE WAS OCCURING.  J.B. WELD WAS APPLIED TO CRACK TO SEAL IT AND DRUM WAS DELIVERED TO CUSTOMER.  SPILLED INK WAS CONTAINED TO INSIDE OF TRAILER AND CLEANED UP WITH OIL DRY ABSORBANT.  ABSORBANT WAS THEN LET DRY.  AFTER DRYING, ABSORBANT WAS DISCARDED IN TRASH DUMPSTER.  FUTURE ACTION TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS WILL BE TO INSPECT DRUMS BEFORE LOADING AT SHIPPER'S DOCK.

CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  JIM LONG OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRANSPORTING A SHIPMENT OF 2 - TRI-WALL CONTAINERS TRAVELLING THROUGH EVANS, NEW YORK ON I-90.  THE DRIVER BECAME AWARE OF MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF HIS TRAILER.  HE PULLED INTO A PAVED REST AREA AND IMMEDIATELY STARTED SPILL CONTROL PROCEDURES TO CONTAIN THE LEAKING MATERIAL.  HE THEN DISCOVERED THAT THE LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM A 1 CUBIC YARD CONTAINER THAT HAD RUPTURED DURING TRANSPORTATION.  THIS CONTAINER WAS DESIGNED TO HOLD SOLID WASTE AND THIS SHIPMENT WAS DESCRIBED BY THE GENERATOR AS A "HAZARDOUS WASTE, SOLID" ON THE MANIFEST.  IT APPEARS THAT THE MAT ERIAL CONTAINED A SIGNIFICANT AMOUNT O LIQUID WHICH SOMEHOW LEAKED THROUGH THE PLASTIC LINER AND SOAKED THE CARDBOARD SHELL UNTIL IT RUPTURED.  SEE ATTACHED REPORT FROM THE DRIVER.

PACKING NUT TIGHTENED WITH 18 INCH PIPE WRENCH, STOPPING LEAK.  THIS CAR WAS EMPTY, ONLY RESIDUE WAS LEAKING FROM VALVE.

PACKING WITHIN THE PUMP WAS BAD, CAUSING SOLVENT TO LEAK FROM THE PUMP, BUT THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN BUCKETS AND WITH ABSORBENT PADS.  WHEN PUMPING WAS COMPLETED, RESIDUAL SOLVENT WAS LEFT IN A HOSE.  THIS MATERIAL WAS RELEASED TO THE GROUND (APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS) WHEN DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO LOAD THE HOSE ONTO THE TRUCK. ALL MATERIAL WAS RELEASED TO THE LOT, WHICH IS COVERED WITH A SLAG (GRAVEL).  THE AREAS OF RELEASE WERE REMEDIATED BY EXCAVATION BY A BACKHOE.  ALL EXCAVATED MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO 16 55 GALLON DRUMS. RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OVERSAW SITE REMEDIATION.  SPILL AREAS WERE MONITORED FOR RESIDUAL AND ALL AREAS TESTED WERE LESS THAT .5 PPM. EXCAVATION AREAS WERE FILLED IN WITH NEW SLAG.  DRUMMED MATERIAL WAS SENT FOR PROCESSING TO SAFETY-KLEEN CORP RECYCLE CENTER IN HEBRON, OHIO.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AT 0230 OF A SPILL IN B-1 BUILDUP AREA.  2 STEEL DRUMS FOUND LEAKING.  SHIPMENT WAS IDENTIFIED AS PAINT UN1263 SHIPMENT WAS TAKEN TO THE DISPOSAL AREA AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.

WHEN DRIVER ARRIVED AT DELIVERY LOCATION, THE PERSON SUPERVISING THE DELIVERY STATED THAT THE 2 TANKS WERE SEPARATE AND HAD NO CONNECTING LINES BETWEEN THEM.  FLEET BILL OF LADING SHOWED TWO 5000 GALLON TANKS. THE PERSON SUPERVISING THE DELIVERY SAID THEY WERE NOT MANIFOLEDED TANKS. FROM WHAT THE GENTLEMEN SAID THERE WAS ENOUGH ROOM FOR PRODUCT.  DRIVER STARTED DROPPING IN TANK 2, HE SAW PRODUCT COME OUT OF TANK #1.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: TANK TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH XYLENE AT PHIBRO CHEMICAL.  THE TRAILER IS ONE SINGLE COMPARTMENT BUT, IS EQUIPPED WITH 3 DOME LIDS.  THE DRIVER NOR THE OPERATOR CHECKED THE REAR DOME LID.  IT WAS FASTENED WITH ONLY ONE BOLT INSTEAD OF FIVE.  THE BOLT BECAME LOOSE AS THE UNIT TURNED INTO THE STREET WHERE SERVICE TRANSPORT CO. TERMINAL IS LOCATED ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPILL OUT.  ALL DRIVERS ARE TRAINED TO BE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE FINAL CHECK OF THEIR EQUIPMENT.  DRIVER WAS DISCIPLINED FOR FAILURE TO DO DO IN THIS CASE.
ONE THE TIME OF UNLOADING MATERIAL THE PAIL WAS FOUND LEAKING VERY LITTLE. THE PAIL WAS SENT TO OS&D WHERE IT WAS IMMEDIATELY STORED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER.

OUR LOADED TRAILER WAS SPOTTED AT DANA TANK WASH ON JULY 2, 1992 FOR DELIVERY JULY 6, 1992.  OUR TERMINAL MANAGER RECEIVED A CALL FROM DANA AT 0900 HRS. ON 7/6/92 ADVISING THAT THE VALVES ON OUR TRAILER WERE OPEN AND THAT IT APPEARED THAT THE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER WAS GONE.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE SEAL ON THE DOME WAS INTACT, THE VALVES WERE OPEN AND THE MATERIAL WAS GONE.  THE AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED AND DUE TO TORRENTIAL RAINS AND THE FACT THE THE PRODUCT IS WATER SOLUBLE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT NO HAZARD EXISTED.  INVESTIGATION IS CONTINUING TO ATTEMPT TO DETERMINE THE RESPONSIBLE PARTY.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY.  HE CONNECTED THE HOSES FOR THE TRANSFER OF MATERIAL TO THE CUSTOMERS STORAGE AND COMMENCED THE TRANFER. DURING THE PROCESS THE EARS ON THE DISCHARGE HOSE WORKED LOOSE AND THE HOSE DISCONNECTED.  OUR DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND NOTIFIED THE CUSTOMER.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AIN A SUMP.  OUR DRIVER RECONNECTED THE HOSE AND COMPLETED THE DELIVERY WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AND PROCEEDED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE.  THE SITE GLASS SHOWED THAT THE STORAGE TANK WAS APPROXIMATELY HALF FULL WHEN IT OVERFLOWED.  OUR DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND HAD TO WAIT FOR THE CUSTOMER TO DRAW DOWN THE STORAGE TANK IR ORDER TO COMPLETE HIS DELIVERY.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS ENROUTE TO HIS DESTINATION.  HE STOPPED A TRUCK STOP FOR COFFEE AND IN CHECKING HIS UNIT NOTED VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE DOME AREA. HE ISOLATED HIS TRAILER AND NOTIFIED THE COMPANY AS WELL AS THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES.  OUR PERSONNEL WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE DOME GASKET WAS NOT SEALING PROPERLY.  A NEW DOME GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE DRIVER CONTINUED TO HIS DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY.

column42: COAL TAR DYE, LIQUID (NOT OTHERWISE SPECIFICALLY NAMED IN 172.101)
column168: ONE (1) 30-GALLON FIBRE DRUM WAS BEING SHIPPED TO THE INTERNATIONAL DYESTUFFS CORPORATION FROM OUR CONCORD TERMINAL IN NEW HAMPSHIRE.  AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL, THE TRAILER WAS IN LINE-HAUL TO OUR NEW JERSEY TERMINAL IN CARLSTADT FOR DELIVERY TO THE FINAL DESTINATION IN CLIFTON, NEW JERSEY. THE DRUM WAS STRAPPED TO A WOODEN PALLET FOR STABILATION.  TWO OF THE BOARDS ON THE PALLET BROKE FROM BOUNCING ON THE BUMPY HIGHWAY AND THE DRUM FELL THROUGH THEM AND THEN FELL OVER AND SPILL INSIDE VEHICLE OCCURRED. STATE POLICE AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO OUR DRIVER'S EMERGENCY CALL REPORTING THE SPILL.  THEY CONTAINED THE SPILL UNTIL THE CLEAN-UP COMPANY ARRIVED SHORTLY THEREAFTER.  VALLERIE SAFETY DIRECTOR AND REGIONAL TERMINAL MANAGER WERE NOTIFIED AND INVOLVED. PREVENTATIVE MEASURES TAKEN TO AVOID FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE INCLUDE THE COUNSELLING OF THE PROPER EMPLOYEES AND SUPERVISORS INVOLVED TO INCLUDE INSTRUCTIONS OF PROPER PACKING AND BLOCKING OF FREIGHT. PALLETS OF SMALL BASE 'WALK' ON THE TRAILER AND ALSO TIP MORE EASILY. FREIGHT SHOULD BE BLOCKED TIGHT WITH OTHER FREIGHT TO PREVENT DAMAGE AND/OR SPILL.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: IT APEARS THAT A PORTION OF THE LIQUID SURFACED DURING TRANSPORTATION. THE VEHICLE MUST NEGOTIATE TWO 90 TURNS, ONE OF WHICH IS AT THE BOTTOM OF A HILL.  DURING THE TURN, SOME THREE GALLONS SPILLED.  THE INCIDENT OCCURRED WITHIN THE SIGHT OF THE T.S.D.F. A RECYCLING OPERATION.  THE T.S.D.F IMMEDIATELY SENT WORKERS AND EQUIPMENT TO THE SCENE UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THEIR ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICER.  THE CLEAN-IP WAS IMMEDIATE AND THOROUGH.

column168: RAIL TANK CAR EN ROUTE FROM NEW ORLEANS, LA TO LAKELAND, FL., WAS SHOPPED IN PENSACOLA, FL BY RAILROAD FOR RUNNING GEAR REPAIR.  WHILE IN SHOP RUPTURE DISC FAILED.  CAR WAS MOVED TO OUTSIDE REMOTE SAFE AREA AND LOAD WAS DUMPED.  NO INJURY OR PROPERTY DAMAGE WAS INVOLVED.

CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM TOP DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS AND PLACED TO ISOLATED TRACK FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR. CHEMTREC, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER ADVISED REPRESENTATIVE WOULD INSPECT AND REPAIR.  SHIPPER TIGHTENED TOP CONTROL OUTLET VALVE AND THEN REPLACED GASKETS ON BOTTOM OUTLET UNLOADING PIPE AND RELEASED CAR TO CONTINUE ITS DESTINATION.

CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING OUT OF TOP DOME DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS AND PLACED TO ISOLATED TRACK FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR. CHEMTREC, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER ADVISED REPRESENTATIVE WOULD INSPECT AND REPAIR.  SHIPPER REPLACED DOME GASKET AND RELEASED CAR TO CONTINUE ITS DESTINATION.

CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM DOME DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS AND PLACED TO ISOLATED TRACK FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR. CHEMTREC, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER ADVISED REPRESENTATIVE WOULD INSPECT AND REPAIR.  SHIPPER REPLACED RUPTURED SAFETY DISK AND VALVE GASKET AND RELEASED TO CONTINUE ITS DESTINATION.

EMPLOYEE SLIPPED CAUSING DRUM TO TIP AGAINST EACH OTHER.  ONE DRUM TIPPED OVER.  METAL CLASP OPENED ALLOWING LID TO FAIL.  8-9 GALS SOLVENT ON TRUCK FLOOR SKIPP KIT/ABSORBENT MATERIAL, CLOTHS/USED FOR CLEAN UP.  ALL MATERIAL DRUMMED AND LABELED.  EMPLOYEE SHOULD BE MORE CAREFUL HANDLING MATERIALS.

PACKAGES WERE REMOVED FROM SORT OPERATIONS BECAUSE OF APPARENT LEAKAGE, STAIN AND ODOR.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER PACKAGES IT WAS DISCOVERED THE INNER PACKAGES CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE OUTSIDE PACKAGES HAD NO MARKINGS OR LABELLING TO INDICATE THE INNER CONTENTS WERE DANGEROUS GOODS.  A SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION WAS ALSO NOT PROVIDED WITH THE SHIPMENTS.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLLUTION CONTROL GROUP WERE CALLED TO ASSIST IN CLEAN UP.  THE CAA IN THE UK WASNOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION WAS CONTACTED IN BRUSSELS WHERE SPECIAL AGENT PATRICK O'FALLON AND FLOYD SEELYE WERE NOTIFIED FOR INSPECTION OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS 1 LITER OF ACETRONITRILE AND 2 1 LITER CONTAINERS OF DIMETHYL SULPHOXIDE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.  A SECOND 3 PIECE SHIPMENT WAS RECEIVED TWO DAYS LATER FROM THE SAME SHIPPER.

column168: CUSTOMERS FREIGHT WAS LOADED IN NOSE OF TRAILER.  NOSE OF TRAILER WAS MADE UP OF A WOODEN BULK HEAD WHICH HAD SPLINTERS. PREVENTION: MEETINGS WILL BE HELD WITH DRIVERS TO USE MORE CAUTION WHEN LOADING HAZ MATERIALS AROUND WOOD. WHILE LOADING HOME HEATING OIL FROM A STORAGE TANK [OIL, NOS, COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID, NA 1270] INTO THE CARGO TANK TANK BY PUMP, APROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS WAS RELEASED THROUGH THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE VENT ONTO THE ASPHALT STREET.  THE VEHICLE WAS PARKED ON A HILL WHICH CAUSED THE OIL FLOW TO THE FRONT OF THE CARGO TANK.  WHEN THE STORAGE TANK WENT EMPTY, THE PUMP FORCED ENOUGH AIR INTO THE CAREGO TANK TO OPEN THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ALLOWING THE OIL TO SPILL THROUGH THE NOW OPEN VENT.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP, NO RELEASE TO THE ENVIRONMENT OCCURRED.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A MAJOR TRAFFIC ACCIDENT WHICH RIPPED OPEN THE DRIVER SIDE OF THE TRUCK, STRIKING ONE DRUM AND RUPTURING IT AT THE BASE. THE RUPTURED DRUM CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 12 GALLONS OF SPENT MATERIAL SPIRITS WHICH SPILLED ONTO THE PAVEMENT AND SOIL ALONGSIDE THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  CLEAN UP EFFORTS WERE BEGUN AS SOON AS POSSIBLE TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB ANY SPILLED MATERIAL WHICH REMAINED ON THE PAVEMENT.  REIDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, OF ROSEMONT, IL WAS CALLED IN TO SCRUB THE PAVEMENT AND REMOVE CONTAMINATED SOIL ALONG THE SHOULDER.  AFTER RESULTS OF SOIL SAMPLES WERE RETURNED, ADDITIONAL SOIL WAS REMOVED ON JULY 15, 1992 AND JULY 17, 1992.  PRESENTLY, THE AREA HAS BEEN DETERMINED TO BE COMPLETELY REMEDIATED,  ALL SPILL CLEAN-UP MATERIALS AND CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS SHIPED TO SAFETY-KLEEN CORPORATION, 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE, SE, HEBRON , OH 43025 FOR DISPOSAL.  THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FLEET GARAGE AT 390 SADLER AVE, ELGIN, IL 60120.  THE EMPTY RUPTURED DRUM AND ALL OTHER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (OF WHICH NONE HAD SPILLED) WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRUCK AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 450 DOMENIC COURT, FRANKLIN PARK, IL 60131.

column168: CLEAN HARBORS OF KINGSTON, INC. TRANSPORTED A 85 GALLON OVERPACK CONTAINING: "RQ WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, CORROSIVE, NOS (D001, D002, D006, D007) FLAMMABLE LIQUID UN 2924 (CONTAINS HEPTANE, HYDROGEN CHLORIDE)" TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO FROM BASF CORPORATION IS WYANDOTTE, MI. STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES DICTATE THAT LESS THAN TRUCK LOAD QUANTITIES DESTINED FOR DISPOSAL AT CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO'S FACILITY BE TRANS-SHIPPED THROUGH CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND TO FULLY UTILIZE THE VEHICLE'S DRUM CAPACITY.  AT TIME OF SHIPMENT FROM SITE OF GENERATION, THE CONTAINER DISPLAYED NO OUTWARD SIGNS OF DETERIORATION.  UPON LOAD CHECK PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM THE RING OF THE OVERPACK AND AN AUDIBLE HISSING NOISE WAS PRESENT.  CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND IMMEDIATELY INITIATED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE PRESSURE BUILD UP AND DEVELOP A HEALTH AND SAFETY PLAN TO SAFELY MANAGE THE DRUM.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE GENERATOR FILLED THE VOID SPACE WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE THUS CAUSING A REACTION BETWEEN THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID PRESENT IN THE INNER CONTAINER.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW THEN INITIATED PROCEDURES TO RELIEVE THE PRESSURE BY PERIODICALLY UNSCREWING THE BUNG CAP.  WHILE THIS PROCEDURE WAS UNDER WAY, THE PRESSURE CAUSED THE NOW LOOSENED BUNG CAP TO POP OFF THE CONTAINER THUS RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 30-40 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  THE EMERGENCY CREW IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED THE SPILLED PRODUCT USING SPEEDI DRY AND PROCEEDED TO DECONTAMINATE THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER.  ALL CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS CONTAINERIZED AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL AT CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE LOCATED IN BRAINTREE, MA.  NO PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED FROM THE WASTE HAULING PORTION OF THE VEHICLE.  THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION WAS RE-OVERPACKED AND SENT TO THE ORIGINAL DESTINATION.  THE OVERPACK THAT FAILED WAS SENT TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE ALONG WITH THE CLEAN-UP DEBRIS.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A SIMILAR INCIDENT IN THE FUTURE, GENERATORS WILL BE QUESTIONED AS TO THE TYPE OF MATERIAL USED TO FILL ALL VOID SPACE TO INSURE THAT IT IS COMPATIBLE WITH THE LADING.  CLEAN HARBORS OF KINGSTON'S DRIVERS WILL ALSO BE INSTRUCTED TO OBTAIN THIS INFORMATION PRIOR TO TRANSPORTING ANY OVERPACKED DRUMS.

column168: TANKER WAS EXITING US RT #1 ONTO THE I-95 RAMP AT APPROX 35 MPH.  UPON ENCOUNTERING A SUDDEN AND UNUSUALLY SHARP CHANGE IN THE CURVITURE OF THE RAMP, THE LIQUID CARGO SURGED AND SHIFTED WHICH RESULTED IN THE POWER UNIT AND TANKER TIPPING AND ROLLING DOWN A 30 DEGREE EMBANKMENT.  DURING THE COURSE OF ROLLING DOWN THE HILL, THE VALVE ROLL-OVER PROTECTION PLATES BUCKLED AND BROKE, THUS CAUSING VALVE DAMAGE ADN THE SUBSEQUENT SPILL. THE SPILL RECEIVED THE MAXIMUM POSSIBLE RESPONSE OF BOTH OUR COMPANY AND THE LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES.  THE LIQUID REMAINING IN THE TANKER WAS PUMPED OFF AND ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED.  IN AN ATTEMPT TO PREVENT REOCCURRENCE WE ARE GOING TO CONTACT MA DOT AND ADVISE THEY POST RECOMMENDED SPEED AND HAZARD ARROW SIGNAGE AT ENTRANCE OF RAMP.  ALSO, I AM GOING TO EMPHASIZE SAFE NEGOTIATION OF ON AND OFF RAMPS IN OUR NEXT DEFENSIVE DRIVING CLASS.  ATTACHED PLEASE FIND THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST CONCERNING THE SPILLED MATERIALS.

ALL THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED, AND PLACED IN A STEEL DRUM FOR RECYCLING OR DISPOSAL.  ALL REPRESENTATIVES WILL BE REMINDED TO CHECK ALL LIDS, RINGS, AND BANDS BEFORE TRANSPORTING ANY DRUMS.

column168: DAMAGE WAS REPORTED TO PSC AT 9:00 P.M.  UPON INSPECTION WE FOUND THAT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED.  THE DRUM HAD THE RED, DOT FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABLE, COVRED WITH THE KRAFT PAPER TAPE.  THERE WAS NO UPS FIVE-APART FORM ON THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS SHIPPOED BARE, WITHOUT A CARTON. THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED PER DOT SPECIFICATIONS AND RET URNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROCEDURES WILL BE REVIEWED BY ORIGIN CUSTOMER SERVICE.

column25: X C LOS ANGELES R D C
column168: HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGE WAS LOADED AT THE BOTTOM OF THE LOAD.  OTHER CARTONS CRUSHED THE PACKAGES AND THE METAL WAS PUNCTURED RESULTING IN LEAKAGE OF MATERIAL.  DAMAGED PORTION WAS DISPOSED OFF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROCEDURE.  HUB MANAGER SHOULD FOLLOW UP WITH LOADERS.

BOX WAS FOUND WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER.  THE CONTENTS WERE REPACKED ACCODING THE UPS SPECIFICATIONS AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  A DAMAGE REPORT AND ISP CARD WERE PREPARED AND SENT TO THE ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR THEIR FOLLOW UP WITH THE SHIPPER.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING FROM MC-306 TRAILER INTO ABOVE GROUND 4,000 GALLON STORAGE TANK, USING CUSTOMERS PUMP.  THE VIBRATION FROM THE PUMP HAD "WALKED" THE VALVE SHUT.  UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS FOUND THAT THE PACKING ON THE VALVE WAS VERY LOOSE.  DRIVER WAS IN ATTENDANCE OF THE DELIVERY, BUT COULD NOT SEE THE STORAGE TANK AS HE WAS ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER-STORAGE TANK WAS ON THE LEFT OF THE TRAILER.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE TANK BERM (UNLEADED GASOLINE.  DRIVER STOPPED DELIVERY, WHEN A MOTORIST DRIVING BY TOLD HIM GASOLINE WAS COMING OUT OF THE TOP OF TANK.  FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY, COMPANY NOTIFIED, ADJUSTOR SENT TO SITE IMMEDIATELY.  CLEAN UP STARTED BY LATE EVENING.

DRUM LOAD IN BACK OF TRUCK SHIFTED CAUSING STRAP TO SLIP SLIGHTLY AND DRUM FELL ON THE STRAP.  TRUCK WAS EMPTIED AND ADDITIONAL ABSORBENTS WERE USED TO SOAK UP LIQUID AND CORNCOB MATERIAL WAS SWEPT OVER FLOOR TO PICK OF RESIDUE.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AT DESTINATION.  HE PROCEEDED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE.  AS OUR TRAILER WENT EMPTY THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED.  THE CUSTOMER TOOK CARE OF THE CLEANUP.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DUE TO NO BLOCKING AND BRACING, THE LOAD SHIFTED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER CAUSING DAMAGE TO THE TRAILER DOORS.  WHEN THE LOAD SHIFTED, 1-2000 BAG OF PRODUCT WAS TORN OPEN, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 10 POUNDS OF PRODUCT.  THE BAG WAS REPAIRED BY SEWING THE RIP WITH NYLON THREAD WITH AN EPOXY RESIN GLUE OVERPATCH.  THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER WAS TRNASFERRED INTO ZTRZ 633237 AND THEN PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED FOR RAILROAD MOVEMENT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM ON STORAGE TANK MALFUNCTIONED CAUSING PRESSURE TO BACK UP[.  WHEN DRIVER TOOK HOSE LOOSE, THE PRESSURE BLEW PRODUCT BACK CAUSING THE SPILL.  FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND PRODUCT CLEANED UP.

column168: UNITS (A) & (B) LOADED IN NOSE OF 27' TRAILER AND PREPARED FOR ADDITIONAL LOADING OF CARGO. IN PROCESS OF MOVING TRAILER, LOAD  BLOCK SHIFTED, ALLOWING TWO UNITS TO ROLL TO BACK OF TRAILER AND FALL TO THE GROUND.  DEWARS WERE IMMEDIATELY STOOD UP-RIGHT AND ALLOWED TO VENT NATURALLY IN OPEN WINDY AREA BEFORE BEING MOVED TO DOCK AREA AND PREPARED FOR RESHIPMENT BACK TO ORIGINAL SHIPPER, PER THEIR DIRECTION.

column168: WHAT HAPPENED! ONE DRUM OF 4 TOTAL WAS REFUSED BY CON'S DUE TO SOME SLIGHT LEAKING ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM SEAL.  AFTER RETURN TO THE FAC TERMINAL, DRIVER MIKE MAYER WAS INSTRUCTED TO REMOVE FROM ROUTE TRAILER AND PLACE ON THE FAC DOCK FOR HANDLING.  (NO SPILL AT THIS POINT).  WHILE ATTEMPTING TO OFF LOAD WITH A DRUM DOLLY THE GAP BETWEEN THE TRAILER AND DOCK CAUSED A "JOLT" PUNCTURING THE PLASTIC DRUM AT BOTTOM RIM.  DRIVER MAYER FAILED TO PULL THE DOCK PLATE PRIOR TO OFF LOADING. LEAKING MATERIAL CLEANED UP BY CONTAINERIZED CHEMICAL CO AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS TAKEN BY CONTAINERIZED CHEMICAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN OVERPACK AND WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER, KEYSTONE ANILINE LOCATED IN SANTA FE SPRINGS, CA. ON PRO 865-328763.

column168: THE MATERIAL WAS BEING REMOVED FROM THE TOP BIN OF THE STORAGE RACK WITH A FORKLIFT.  AS THE SKID CLEARED THE SHELVES, TWO CARTONS FELL APPROXIMATELY 12 FEET TO THE CONCRETE FLOOR.  THE CARTONS WERE PLACED BACK ON THE SKID AND TAKEN TO THE DOCK AREA.  UPON REACHING THE DOCK CONTENTS WERE LEACKING FROM ONE CARTON.  (ANOTHER CARTON WAS FOUND TO BE DAMAGED UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, HOWEVER, THE CONTENTS WERE CONTAINED WITHIN THE CARTON). WHEN THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS NOTICED, THE AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY ROPED OFF AND THE AIRPORT AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.  THE AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT TOOK CONTROL OF THE SITUATION AND MONITORED THE AREA AROUND THE SPILL UNTIL THE AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY I.T. CORPORATION AT 1525 HRS. TO AVOID SUCH INCIDENTS IN THE FUTURE, DANGEROUS GOODS WILL NOT BE STORED ON THE THIRD LEVEL OF OUR STORAGE RACKS.  ALSO ANY MATERIAL STACKED GREATER THEN ONE TIER WILL BE SECURED TO THE OTHER CRGO AND SKID.

column168: WHILE TRAVELING SOUTH ON H IGHWAY 13 APPROXIMATELY FIVE (5) MILES SOUTH OF EUNICE, LOUISIANA, HYDROGEN TRAILER S/N  13055 OVERTURNED.  THE PRODUCT REMAINED SECURE WITHIN THE TRAILER.  THERE WAS NO PRODUCT RELEASED TO ATMOSPHERE DURING THE ACCIDENT.  DURING CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS, THE PRESSURE WITHIN THE DAMAGED TRAILER ROSE TO 17 PSIG.  A DECISION WAS MADE BY AIR PRODUCTS' PERSONNEL TO VENT BACK DOWN TO 1 PSIG BEFORE ALLOWING THE CRANES TO UPRIGHT THE TRAILER.  THIS PROCEDURE RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 2000 STD CUBIC FEET OF HYDROGEN GAS INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.

PRODUCT CONTINUED TO FLOW INTO THE PUMP, LEAKED OUT THRU THE PUMP WHERE GASKET FAILED.  DRIVER REVERSED PUMP TO PUMP MATERIAL BACK INTO THE TANKER.  MEANWHILE, ANOTHER TANKER WAS DISPATCHED TRO SIGHT AND PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF AND PUT INTO THIS TANKER, DURING A TIME PERIOD OF ABOUT 2 HOURS FROM THE TIME TANKER WAS DISPATCHED UNTI PRODUCT TRANSFERRED.  ABOUT 200 GALLONS FLOWED ON TO CLASS 5 GRAVEL IN GRAVEL PIT.  AREA WAS DIKED. ABOUT 170 GALLONS WERE SUCKED UP INTO GOOD TANKER AND PUMPED INTO CUSTOMERS TANK.  REMAINING 30 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WERE MIXED IN WITH GRAVEL AND PUT IN CUSTOMERS STOCKPILE TO BE USED AS ROAD MATERIAL.

column168: WHILE CONDUCTING TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS (SSA/HM) D.A. LOW NOTED FLIX 2590 HAD LIQUID STAINS ON BOTH SIDES. INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE VENT.  BS&B, 100 PSI, FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED.  DISC WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW BS&B, 100 PSI, FRANGIBLE DISC WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  SEAL UPC-54622 WAS APPLIED TO THE VENT.  JIM LONG OF CHEMTREC AND ED ERYING OF F.S. INDUSTRIES LIMITED WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

WHILE CONDUCTING TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D.A. LOW NOTED TANK CAR PLMX 33350 LEAKING FROM THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON GAUGING ROD.  SSA/HM LOW TIGHTENED THE PACKING GLAND NUT 3/4 OF A TURN WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  JEFF BOTWINICK OF CHEMTREC AND KEN MCMILLEN OF CENEX WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE, WAS NOTIFIED BY EAST BOWL YARDMASTER ADVISING THAT CAR NDYX 35306 HAD A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA NEAR CAR.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE VAPOR VALVE PORT PLUG AND BOTH LIQUID LINE VALVES PORT PLUGS WERE NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  ALSO, THE SLIP TUBE GAUGE ROD VALVE WAS OPEN.  MANAGER STINE SECURED ALL PLUGS AND GAUGE ROD.  SULPHUR STICK WAS THEN USED TO CHECK FOR LEAKS.  NO INDICATION OF LEAKAGE WAS NOTED AND CAR WAS RELEASED.  JOE DEBMAN OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT, REPORT NUMBER 16290.

MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE, WAS NOTIFIED THAT A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA WAS NOTED NEAR A CUT OF SIX TANK CARS. CHIEF INSPECTOR, A.D. MATY, AAR, WAS CONTACTED FOR ASSISTANCE.  LEAKING CAR WAS SUSPECTED TO BE UTLX 99124 BUT INSPECTION OF CAR DETERMINED NO LEAKAGE.  DURING VISUAL INSPECTION ON TOP OF CAR GATX 97847, A STRONG ODOR AND HISSING SOUND NEAR THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WERE NOTED.  INSPECTION DETERMINED A VAPOR LEAK FROM THE BASE OF THE VAPOR VALVE.  AFTER SECURING THE TWO OUTSIDE NUTS ON THE VALVE BASE, LEAK STOPPED.  CHECKED WITH "SNOOP" AND "SULPHUR STICK" AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED.  SEAL UP-X 140932 WAS APPLIED AND CAR WAS RELEASED.  JOE DEBMAN OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT, REPORT #16190.

AT 0238 SORT AREA MGR, TERESA WALLS, REPORTED A LEAKING SHIPMENT AND THERE WERE 2 EMPLOYEES INVOLVED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, I, TONY FRYE, HAZMAT COORD & P/T SPILL SPECIALIST, RANDY WILLIAMS FOUND 2 WHITE FIBERBOARD BOXES.  BOTH FIBERBOARD BOXES SHOWED SIGNS OF BEING WET. SPECIALIST WILLIAMS PH'D THE WET AREAS & THE PH PAPER TURNED RED, WHICH INDICATES THIS WAS A STRONG ACID.  OPENED THE 1 FIBERBOARD BOX & INSIDE WERE EMPTY STERILE SPECIMEN CONTAINERS.  SPECIALIST WILLIAMS OPENED THE 2ND ONE & FOUND INSIDE 5 - 25ML PLASTIC CONTAINERS IN A PLASTIC ZIPLOCK BAG.  ON THE LABEL OF EACH ONE OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINER AS "HYDROCHLORIC ACID".  EACH PLASTIC CONTAINER HAD SCREW TYPE CLOSURES WITH NO MEANS TO SECURE THEM.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL INSIDE THE PLASTIC ZIPLOCK BAG & THERE WAS NO PROPER ORIENTATION OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINERS.  THESE PLASTIC CONTAINERS WERE PLACED ON TOP OF 4 - 1 GALLON EMPTY PLASTIC CONTAINERS.  APPROX 1 OZ OF THE ACID LEAKED OUT.  THE 2 EMPLOYEES THAT CAME INTO CONTACT WERE NOT EXPERIENCING ANY TYPE OF MEDICAL PROBLEMS. THERE WAS NO ORIENTATION MARKING ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PKGS TO INDICATE THE TOP.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED HAZADOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS IN THE CORROSIVE CABINET PENDING INVESTIGATION & RELEASE BY THE FAA.

TRAINMASTER JOHN ANDERSON REPORTED, CREW OBSERVED TANK CAR LEAKING FROM TOP AT YARD IN RALEIGH NC CAR WAS ISOLATED.  ANDERSON CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE, MALLINCKRODT, WHO RESPONDED PEOPLE TO REPAIR THE CAR.  THE DOUND CAR HAD A BLOWN RUPTURE DISC AND REPLACED IT.  ALSO FOUND LEAK AT WELD SEAM WHERE SAFETY VENT ASEMBLY IS WELD NOT LOAD UNTIL REPAIRED AND MOVED SHORT DISTANCE TO CONSIGNEES FACILITY FOR UNLOADING.

SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT CHICAGO CONSOLIDATED CENTER ON TRAILER 19-2810.  UPON UNLOADING BY DOCKMAN, BILL SNYDER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS LEAKING.  BOTH CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER/NORAC WAS CONTACTED.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND CONTAINED IN RECOVERY DRUM AND WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED THAT SWITCH CREW REPORTED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA NEAR CAR NDYX 35346.  CAR WAS ISOLATED ON TRACK 3. A CAULKING GUN WAS USED TO APPLY SILICONE AROUND THE ENTIRE MANWAY COVER PLATE WHICH STOPPED RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  CAR WAS THEN CLEANED AND RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D.A. LOW WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANK CAR TLDX 114041 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP AREA.  SSA/HM LOW RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE FOUR NUTS AND BOLTS ON THE ONE INCH AIR CONNECTION BLIND FLANGE WERE LOOSE AND ALSO THAT THE GASKET WAS MISSING.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE BLIND FLANGE SAFETY CHAIN WAS LODGED AGAINST THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE, ALLOWING VALVE TO REMAIN IN THE OPEN POSITION.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND FITTING PROPERLY SECURED WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.  JEFF BOTWINICK OF CHEMTREC AND DEE BIRD OF NUWEST WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

HILL WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  SSA/HM HILL'S INSPECTION OF BALDKNOB YARD DETERMINED THAT TANK CAR RAIX 9079 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET ABOUT THREE DROPS PER MINUTE. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED THAT FRA INSPECTOR, BRUCE MARRIOTT, HAD REPORTED CAR CHVX 180035 WAS LEAKING IN EVANSTON YARD. I WAS DRIVING AROUND THE PERIMETER ROAD AND I NOTICED THE EDCX 6030 TANK CAR WAS LEAKING VAPORS FROM THE TOP DOME.  THIS WAS AT 10:15 PM.  WHEN THE 4:00 PM HUMP FINISHED HIS CUT ON THE NORTH HUMP I HAD THEM CROSS OVER TO 064 TRACK WHERE I COUPLED UP FOUR CARS IN ORDER TO TAKE THE EDCX 6030 TANK CAR AND ISOLATE IT IN C YARD IN 126 TRACK ON THE WEST END.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AT 12:15 AM.  I CALLED THE NIGHT SUPERINTENDENT AT MONSANTA AT SAUGET, ILLINOIS, MR. ERC LEE, AND HE SUGGESTED TO LEAVE THE CAR SIT AND THE VALVE SHOULD RESEAT ITSELF IN ONE HOUR'S TIME.  THIS WAS AT 12:30 AM. I CONTACTED MR. SHUPE AT 12:48 AM AND HE STATED HE WOULD COME OUT AND INSPECT THE CAR.  MR. SHUPE ARRIVED AT 2:05 AM AND SECURED CAR AT 4:30 AM.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) C.D. HUGGINS WAS NOTIFIED THAT TRAIN NPSC-25 HAD DERAILED AND TANK CAR NATX 29277 WAS REPORTED LEAKING. SA/HM HUGGINS INSPECTED THE CAR AND NOTED THE REPAIR TO BE HOLDING AND NO OTHER LEAKS WERE FOUND.  CAR WAS SUSTAINED DAMAGED DURING THE DERAILMENT BUT APPEARED IN TACT.  SSA/HM LOW ALSO RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AND UPON HIS ARRIVAL VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS REMOVED AND A SOLID PLUG WAS PLACED IN THE FITTING TO PREVENT ANY RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT DURING HANDLING AND TRANSFER.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

DOCKMAN ERIC STUDE WAS MOVING THE SHIPMENT WITH A FORKLIFT. THE SHIPMENT WAS SHRUNK WRAPPED ON A PALLET. HE WAS DRIVING DOWN THE DOCK AND MISJUDGED THE CORNER. HE TURNED TOO EARLY AND RAMMED THE PALLET ONTO A POLE ON THE DOCK. TWO 5 GAL PAILS BURSTED OPEN SPILLING FLAMMABLE LIQUID ON THE DOCK. THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID WAS CLEANED UP OFF THE DOCK WITH FLOOR DRY AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY PAIL.

column168: APPROXIMATELY 1450 HOURS ON 7-31-92, ASST TRAINMASTER CALLED AND SAID AT WICHITA A TANK CAR UCLX 30111 IS LEAKING HYDROCHLORIC ACID IN YARD ON TRACK 01-09.  SWITCH CREW SET CAR TO TRACK 01-25 SO IT WOULD BE ACCESSIBLE.  THE LEAK WAS ON RIGHT SIDE TANK CAR ABOUT THREE FEET FROM TOP OF TANK ON B END OF LADDER AND WAS LEAKING ABOUT ONE QUART EVERY 10 MINUTES.  APPLIED A 50 GAL PLASTIC TRASH CONTAINER UNDER LEAK AND USED ANOTHER ONE WITH WATER AND SODA ASH SOLUTION WITH A HOSE INTO IT FROM THE TANK CAR TO BLEED OFF PRESSURE ON THE TANK CAR.  APPLIED A 6X6 RUBBER PATCH OVER THE LEAK ON THE TANK WITH A BAND ROUND THE TANK AND TIGHTENED BAND.  THIS SLOWED LEAK TO A DRIP.  CAR UCLX 30111 THEN TRANSFERRED CONTENTS TO TANK CAR UCLX 30025.  ALL SPILLAGE NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND TESTED WITH COLORED STICKS.  NOTE: CAR UCLX 30111 WAS PICKED UP OFF KSW INTERCHANGE AT 1030 HOURS WITH NO LEAK DETECTED. SWITCHMAN C D HARLAN, FILE 01-0792-014 WHILE WALKING CUT ON ROUTINE DUTIES INHALED VAPORS, EXAMINED , GIVEN RX MEDROL DOSEPAK AND RELEASED.
